### Throughput

In this section I've executed the reconstruction using a varying number of threads, between 1 and 16, and a varying number of streams, between 1 and nThreads. The number of events is 4 times the number of streams.
The throughput has been measured by the framework's timing module.






```python
import pandas as pd
from matplotlib import cm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib notebook
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns



```


```python
df = pd.read_csv("https://www.cern.ch/felice.pantaleo/throughput.csv")

threads = df.T.values[0]
streams = df.T.values[1]
throughput = df.T.values[2]

cm = plt.cm.get_cmap('RdYlBu')
sc = plt.scatter(threads, streams, c=throughput, vmin=0.005, vmax=0.05, s=70, cmap=cm)
colorbar = plt.colorbar(sc)
colorbar.set_label('throughput (ev/s)')
plt.xlabel("number of threads")
plt.ylabel("number of streams")
```

```python
points = df.values
streams2 = []
streams4 = []
streams6 = []
streams8 = []

for p in points:
    if p[1] ==2:
        streams2.append([p[0],p[2]])
    elif p[1] ==4:
        streams4.append([p[0],p[2]])
    elif p[1] ==8:
        streams8.append([p[0],p[2]])
    elif p[1] ==6:
        streams6.append([p[0],p[2]])


streams2T = list(map(list, zip(*streams2)))
streams4T = list(map(list, zip(*streams4)))
streams6T = list(map(list, zip(*streams6)))
streams8T = list(map(list, zip(*streams8)))
fig2 = plt.figure()


a = plt.plot(streams2T[0],streams2T[1], label='2 streams')
a = plt.plot(streams4T[0],streams4T[1], label='4 streams')
a = plt.plot(streams6T[0],streams6T[1], label='6 streams')
a = plt.plot(streams8T[0],streams8T[1], label='8 streams')
plt.xlabel("number of threads")
plt.ylabel("throughput")
plt.legend()


```

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="800">





    <matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f03dec638d0>



The throughput depends on the size of the thread pool and the amount of parallel work available. 
When only two events are "flying", there is not enough concurrent work to do, and the throughput saturates already with 8 threads.
Things slightly improve by increasing the number of events in flight to 4.
Increasing the number of concurrent streams from 6 to 8 does not affect much the throughput for a number of threads smaller than 16. With a higher number of threads, they will saturate at different points.




## Moving to memory-centric processing?
Memory has become more and more expensive and today, it is the main driver for the cost of computing hardware.
This section aims at demonstrating that, setting the number of streams depending on the amount of memory available, and then use the available threads is a cost-effective approach.

In order to evaluate the performance for a fixed-size thread pool, one can study how the throughput changes when varying the number of concurrent streams.

For 8 threads, throughput saturates already at 4 streams, and it is pointless to use more streams which will only affect memory usage.
For a thread pool consisting of 16 threads, performance saturates at 6 streams.


```python
points = df.values
threads8 = []
threads16= []


for p in points:
    if p[0] ==8:
        threads8.append([p[1],p[2]])
    elif p[0] ==16:
        threads16.append([p[1],p[2]])


threads8T = list(map(list, zip(*threads8)))
threads16T = list(map(list, zip(*threads16)))

fig3 = plt.figure()


b = plt.plot(threads8T[0],threads8T[1], label='8 threads')
b = plt.plot(threads16T[0],threads16T[1], label='16 threads')
plt.xlabel("number of streams")
plt.ylabel("throughput")
plt.legend()


```

I have studied the memory footprint of a threadpool of 16 threads, when processing the same number of events, when using 6 or 16 streams. As shown above, the throughput is the basically the same. Below, one can see that jobs starts and end at the same time. 
However, the memory footprint is almost three times higher when processing using 16 streams with respect to 6 streams.

### Conclusion
We should re-evaluate the choice of setting the number of streams equals to the number of threads.
A data-centric (or memory-centric) approach would be more efficient:
-2.5GB of memory are needed per stream
-A number of threads up to a factor of two higher than the number of streams is beneficial

One can obtain the same throughput of:
- 24 physical cores, threads
- 24 streams
- 72GB memory

with:
- 24 physicsl cores, threads
- 9 streams
- ~30GB memory

Increasing parallelism/concurrency within a stream would improve this efficiency and one should aim to do that.
